value.value: A functional area or structure in a cell that is not enclosed in a membrane.
An area on the periphery of the retina, located anterior to the ora serrata, which is composed of pigmented epithelium.
A cell found naturally, in any part of the body that is free from disease.

An anatomical structure, which consists of similarly specialized cells and intercellular matrix, aggregated according to genetically determined spatial relationships. Examples: epithelium, muscle tissue, connective tissue, neural tissue, lymphoid tissue.
One of the two channels of the nose, from the point where they divide to the external opening.
A mucosal erosion that occurs in the esophagus, stomach or duodenum. Symptoms can include abdominal pain, nausea and vomiting, and bleeding.
An intermediate filament located in the nucleus of a cell, which plays a role in the maintenance of nuclear structure.
Heterochromatin that is associated with the nucleolus.
A thread-like complex of ribosomal components including ribosomal RNA, in various stages of transcription, and associated proteins.
A collection of preribosomes in the nucleolus.
The irregular network or rows of fine ribonucleoprotein granules or microfilaments forming most of the nucleolus.

label.value: Nucleus of the Mesencephalic Tract of the Trigeminal Nerve

value.value: A collection of cell bodies of cranial nerve V, extending from the chief sensory nucleus through the midbrain, that connect to primary afferents receiving proprioceptive input from the face.

label.value: Nucleus of the Spinal Tract of the Trigeminal Nerve

value.value: The site of termination for fibers of the spinal trigeminal tract, located in the lateral medulla and extending in into the caudal pons, that receives input from the ipsilateral face via somatic afferent fibers for touch, pain, and temperature.
Any artery that supplies the inner cavity of a long bone.
Fluid collection within the pericardial sac, usually due to inflammation.
An artery arising from the anterior or posterior trunk of the internal iliac artery that supplies the ilium and pubic bones as well as the obturator and adductor muscles.

A striated muscle located on the anterior surface of the pelvis, with its origin on the obturator foramen and obturatory membrane and insertion on the trochanteric fossa of the femur, which functions to laterally rotate the femur.

A striated muscle covering the majority of the lateral wall of the pelvis, with its origin on the ischiopubic ramus and obturator membrane and insertion on the greater trochanter, which functions to externally rotate the hip.
One of two muscles located in the pelvis: the obturator externus muscle or the obturator internus muscle.
An artery arising from the external carotid artery that branches into the auricular, arteria princeps cervicis, meningeal, muscular, and sterno-mastoid arteries.

label.value: Occipital Horn of the Lateral Ventricle

value.value: The part of the lateral ventricle that projects posteriorly into the occipital lobe.
Any one of the narrow grooves located on the surface of the occipital lobe of the brain.

A convolution located with fractions in both the occipital and temporal lobes of the brain, which is bound by the lingual (medial occipitotemporal) gyrus and parahippocampal gyrus superiorly, and the inferior temporal gyrus inferiorly.

A striated muscle of the scalp comprised of a frontal and occipital belly, extending from the superior nuchal line posteriorly to the skin of the eyebrows anteriorly and inserting into the epicranial aponeurosis, which functions to move the scalp and wrinkle the forehead.

A group of extrinsic muscles that are responsible for moving the eye and lifting the eyelid. These include: superior rectus, inferior rectus, medial rectus, inferior oblique, and levator palpebrae superioris, all innervated by CN III (oculomotor nerve), superior oblique, innervated by CN IV (trochlear nerve), lateral rectus, innervated by CN VI (abducens nerve).

The carbonic salt of calcium (CaCO3). Calcium carbonate is used therapeutically as a phosphate buffer in hemodialysis, as an antacid in gastric hyperacidity for temporary relief of indigestion and heartburn, and as a calcium supplement for preventing and treating osteoporosis. (NCI04)
A prominence at the proximal end of the ulna. It forms the tip of the elbow.
Sensory receptors located in the olfactory epithelium in the nasal cavity that respond to airborne chemicals.

A pair of microanatomical triangular shaped spaces located in the superficial part of each olfactory sulcus, which contain the olfactory nerves and the orbitofrontal branches of the anterior cerebral arteries.

An epithelium located in the roof, superior conchae, and septum of the nasal cavity. It is formed by ciliated olfactory receptor cells, supporting cells and basal cells. Olfactory glands in the epithelium produce and secrete mucus which forms a layer over the epithelium. The cilia of the receptor cells protrude into the mucous layer where molecular reception with odors occurs and sensory transduction begins.

A small, rounded neural structure involved in olfaction, which is located at the anterior end of the olfactory sulcus on the orbital surface of the frontal lobe, and which is attached to the rest of the brain by the olfactory tract.
The part of the nasal mucosa composed of neuroepithelial tissue and mucus-producing Bowman's glands. The mucus moistens the epithelium and helps dissolve odor-containing gases.

A fissure or narrow groove running rostrocaudally on the anterior surface of each frontal lobe of the brain separating the gyrus rectus from the medial orbital gyrus and containing the olfactory bulb and tract.

A white band comprising axons originating in the olfactory bulb and running caudally along the orbital surface of each frontal lobe that terminate in the primary olfactory cortex at the base of the cerebral hemisphere.
A fold of peritoneum originating at the stomach and supporting the viscera.
A benign or malignant neoplasm arising from a peripheral nerve or the perineural sheaths.
The specialized plasma membrane of an oocyte.
The specialized cytoplasm in an oocyte.
A chamber, continuous with collections of mastoid cells throughout the mastoid portion of the temporal bone, connecting the tympanic cavity with the mastoid process.
The hole in the left atrium of the heart where the pulmonary vein enters.
The orifices through which the superior and inferior vena cava drain blood into the right atrium.
The first and smallest of three divisions of the trigeminal nerve, which carries only sensory fibers supplying innervation to the forehead, scalp, lacrimal gland, eye, and side of the nose.

An artery arising from the internal carotid artery that branches into two groups of vessels; the orbital group that supplies the orbit and surrounding parts and the ocular group that supplies the globe and muscles of the eye.
The bundle of optic nerve fibers that cross to the opposite side of the brain at the optic chiasm.

A continuation of the optic nerves just dorsal to the optic chiasm, formed by temporal fibers of the ipsilateral optic nerve and nasal fibers of the contralateral optic nerve, that carries axons to nuclei within the thalamus and relays visual information to the primary visual cortex of the occipital lobe.
An annular zone of the ciliary body continuous with the retina at the ora serrata and covered with ciliary plicae.

A benign or malignant neoplasm that affects the peritoneum.  Representative examples of benign neoplasms include adenomatoid tumor and disseminated peritoneal leiomyomatosis.  Representative examples of malignant neoplasms include primary peritoneal carcinoma, metastatic carcinoma to the peritoneum, and malignant mesothelioma.
